"Jones A., Slingo A.","Climate model studies of sulphate aerosols and clouds",1997,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","352","1350",,"221","229",,,10.1098/rstb.1997.0017,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030830856&partnerID=40&md5=bbb29025a9ff60ba2527212d74557c40","Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Meteorological Office, London Road, Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom","Jones, A., Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Meteorological Office, London Road, Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom; Slingo, A., Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Meteorological Office, London Road, Bracknell, Berkshire RG12 2SY, United Kingdom","It is generally believed that increases in the atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases as a result of man's activities are leading to global warming. It is also believed that the same activities lead to increasing concentrations of sulphate aerosol, which act to cool the estimate system and ameliorate the warming. The sulphate cooling may be separated into the direct effect in cloud-free regions and the indirect effect in cloudy regions. This paper summarizes recent work at the Hadley Centre on the indirect effect. Results from two versions of the Hadley Centre Climate Model are shown, using various parameterizations linking the amount of sulphate aerosol and the number concentration of droplets in water clouds. These results illustrate the considerable uncertainties in estimating the indirect effect. It is shown that other naturally occurring components of the aerosol population, in particular sea salt, may be important in reducing the magnitude of the indirect effect.",,"anthropogenic aerosol; cloud droplet; greenhouse gas; sulphate aerosol",,,,,,"Andreae, M.O., Elbert, W., De Mora, S.J., Biogenic sulfur emissions and aerosols over the tropical South Atlantic. 3: Atmospheric dimethylsulfide, aerosols and cloud condensation nuclei (1995) J. Geophys. Res., 100, pp. 11335-11356; Blanchard, D.C., Cipriano, R.J., Biological regulation of climate (1987) Nature, Lond., 330, p. 526; Boucher, O., Lohmann, U., The sulfate-CCN-cloud albedo effect: A sensitivity study with two general circulation models (1995) Tellus B, 47, pp. 281-300; Bower, K.N., Choularton, T.W., A parametrization of the effective radius of ice free clouds for use in global climate models (1992) Atmos. Res., 27, pp. 305-339; Bower, K.N., Choularton, T.W., Latham, J., Nelson, J., Baker, M.B., Jensen, J., A parametrization of warm clouds for use in atmospheric general circulation models (1994) J. Atmos. Sci., 51, pp. 2722-2732; Charlson, R.J., Lovelock, J.E., Andreae, M.O., Warren, S.J., Oceanic phytoplankton, atmospheric sulphur, cloud albedo and climate (1987) Nature, Lond., 326, pp. 655-661; Charlson, R.J., Schwartz, S.E., Hales, J.M., Cess, R.D., Coakley, J.A., Hansen, J.E., Hofmann, D.J., Climate forcing by anthropogenic aerosols (1992) Science, Wash., 255, pp. 423-430; Charlson, R.J., Heintzenbcrg, J., (1995) Aerosol Forcing of Climate, , John Wiley & Sons; Cullen, M.J.P., The unified forecast/climate model (1993) Met. Mag., 122, pp. 81-94; Edwards, J.M., Slingo, A., Studies with a flexible new radiation code. I : Choosing a configuration for a large-scale model (1996) Q. Jl R. Met. Soc., 122, pp. 689-719; Han, Q., Rossow, W.B., Lacis, A.A., Near-global survey of effective droplet radii in liquid water clouds using ISCCP data (1994) J. Clim., 7, pp. 475-1197; Hansen, J.E., Travis, L.D., Light scattering in planetry atmospheres (1974) Space Sci. Rev., 16, pp. 527-610; Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Bruce, J., Lee, H., Callander, B.A., Haites, E., Harris, N., Maskell, K., (1995) Climate Change 1994: Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and An Evaluation of the IPCC 7592 Emission Scenarios, , Cambridge University Press; Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Callander, B.A., Harris, N., Kattenberg, A., Maskell, K., (1996) Cl